To conditionally redirect to HTTPS or use HTTP based on the `server.ssl.enabled` setting in your Spring Boot application, need to modify your `SecurityFilterChain` configuration and create a custom `SecurityFilterChain` that checks the value of **server.ssl.enabled** and configures the channel security accordingly.

Here is the sample code : 
```java
@Configuration
public class SecurityConfig {

    @Bean
    public SecurityFilterChain defaultSecurityFilterChain(HttpSecurity httpSecurity) throws Exception {
        // Configure the security filter chain for the default behavior.
        return httpSecurity
            .authorizeRequests(authorizeRequests -&gt;
                authorizeRequests
                    .anyRequest().permitAll() // Allow all requests
            )
            .build();
    }

    @Bean
    public SecurityFilterChain secureSecurityFilterChain(HttpSecurity httpSecurity) throws Exception {
        // Configure the security filter chain for secure (HTTPS) requests.
        return httpSecurity
            .requiresChannel(channelConfigurer -&gt;
                channelConfigurer
                    .requestMatchers(request -&gt; request.getHeader(&quot;X-Forwarded-Proto&quot;) != null)
                    .requiresSecure() // Require HTTPS
            )
            .authorizeRequests(authorizeRequests -&gt;
                authorizeRequests
                    .anyRequest().permitAll() // Allow all secure requests
            )
            .build();
    }

    @Bean
    public SecurityFilterChain securityFilterChain(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
        // Conditionally choose between the default or secure security filter chain
        if (Boolean.parseBoolean(System.getProperty(&quot;server.ssl.enabled&quot;, &quot;false&quot;))) {
            return secureSecurityFilterChain(http);
        } else {
            return defaultSecurityFilterChain(http);
        }
    }
}
```
Replace the &quot;X-Forwarded-Proto&quot; header check with the appropriate header if your application is behind a reverse proxy or load balancer that handles HTTPS termination. This header check is commonly used when such intermediaries are involved.

Using this configuration, your Spring Boot application will redirect to HTTPS only when `server.ssl.enabled` is set to true, and it will use HTTP when `server.ssl.enabled` is set to false.

